Using litterfall nets to study enhanced rock weathering
                    Isabella L. Steeley 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0009-0002-3544-58111

Nature Reviews Earth & Environment

(2026)Cite this article

Subjects

            Carbon cycleClimate-change mitigation

Access through your institution







                        Buy or subscribe

The Brazilian Atlantic rainforest is among the top five global biodiversity hotspots, but it is also one of the most degraded and fragmented tropical forests, with only 24% of its natural range remaining. Cultivating cacao as an understory tree in a forest-like environment, known locally as ‘cabruca’, can improve forest connectivity. This agroforestry system can preserve endemic tree species and increase organic carbon storage, and holds cultural value for the region. However, cabrucas are often lower-yielding than monoculture systems. Enhanced rock weathering — a climate mitigation strategy that involves applying crushed silicate rocks to agricultural soils to capture CO₂ — could establish a credible pathway to access carbon financing while potentially improving soil health and productivity, but the impact of rock-dust spreading on ecosystem health needs to be monitored.Litterfall nets are being used in a field trial in Bahia, Brazil, to explore the consequences of using enhanced rock weathering to offset cacao production emissions. The applied silicate rocks can have a ‘liming’ effect, which increases nutrient availability by raising the pH of the soil, and can supplement fertilizers by adding minerals that contain phosphorus and potassium. Improved understanding of these effects could encourage cacao farmers to adopt the practice, attract investment for rural economies and help to maintain forest connectivity.



